{"title_page": "American Champion Three-Year-Old Male Horse", "text_new": "The '''American Champion Three-Year-Old Male Horse''' is an [[United States|American]] [[Thoroughbred]] [[horse racing]] honor awarded annually in Thoroughbred [[flat racing]]. It became part of the [[Eclipse Award]]s program in 1971.\n\nThe award originated in 1936 when both ''Turf & Sports Digest'' (TSD) the ''[[Daily Racing Form]]'' (DRF) began naming an annual champion. Starting in 1950, the Thoroughbred Racing Associations (TRA) began naming its own champion. The following list provides the name of the horses chosen by these organizations. The only disagreement came in 1968, when Turf & Sports Digest named [[Forward Pass (horse)|Forward Pass]] as champion whereas the other two organizations voted for [[Stage Door Johnny]].\n\nChampions from 1887 through 1935 were selected retrospectively by a panel of experts as published by ''[[The Blood-Horse magazine]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bloodhorse.com/eclipsewinners/pdf/History_Charts.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=August 27, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120904120526/http://www.bloodhorse.com/eclipsewinners/pdf/History_Charts.pdf |archive-date=September 4, 2012 |url-status=bot: unknown |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThere were Co-Champions chosen retrospectively for 1876, 1882, 1885, 1886, 1888, 1893, 1894, 1904, 1906, 1917, 1923, and 1932.\n\nThe ''Daily Racing Form'', the Thoroughbred Racing Associations, and the National Turf Writers Association all joined forces in 1971 to create the Eclipse Award.\n\nAs of 2018, Bob Baffert won the award 9 times as a trainer. No other train won the award more than twice.<ref>{{cite news|first=Jon|last=White|url=https://www.xpressbet.com/component/content/article/11-xb360/xb-blog/4021-an-extraordinary-feat-largely-unnoticed |title=An Extraordinary Feat Largely Unnoticed |publisher=Xpressbet |date=January 30, 2019 |accessdate=2019-01-30}}</ref>\n\n==Honorees==\n\n===Eclipse Awards